A Data Science Pipeline Tutorial on Fertility¶

Author: Diana Shin
Version: May 7th, 2021

Introduction¶

Welcome to my data science pipeline tutorial, where I will be showing how to work with data from collection to analysis. The fertility dataset I will be using is from the University of California, Irvine Machine Learning Repository https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Fertility. This is a great repository to try out exploratory data analysis, and you can filter out datasets so that they are small and have anywhere from 10, to 100 or more columns/variables.

Here is a link to the UC Irvine repository: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/index.php. I recommend a few datasets that are interesting and have different types of data (categorical, numerical, words, etc):

  • Tic-tac-toe, categorical play data that fits decision trees: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Tic-Tac-Toe+Endgame
  • Credit approval, a mix of categorical data and numerical data prime for exploratory data analysis: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Credit+Approval
  • NSF research abstracts, a bag of words of various abstracts that received NSF awards, I recommend using the Natural Language Processing Toolkit (nltk) http://www.nltk.org/book/ with this project: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/NSF+Research+Award+Abstracts+1990-2003

This tutorial will be organized to the following pipeline:
Data Collection
Data Processing
Exploratory Analysis and Data Visualization
Analysis, Hypothesis Testing, and ML
Insight and Policy Decision

Motivation¶

For this data science pipeline tutorial, I chose this dataset because it had a mix of numerical and categorical data. In addition, it is an interesting topic to explore. Typically, we hear about fertility, but how much do we know about it? This dataset has a collection of approximately 100 semen samples from volunteers based on WHO standards, with variables ranging from their sitting and drinking habits, whether their fertility is normal, etc. From a CDC statistic survey in 2018, there were about 4 million births in 2014. This tutorial could be helpful in exploring what could be helpful to the millions of people wanting to have a child. Let's explore!

Data Collection¶

To get the data from the UCI Machine Learning Repository, you could download the data from the Data Folder link, or you can use the os library to grab the data automatically. I am running on Linux, so I will be using wget to grab the dataset. There are lots of commands to work with your system as you grab and handle data, so I recommend looking at https://ss64.com/bash/ if you are on a Linux system to get familiar with the commands used in this tutorial.

However, I noticed that the column descriptions are not really complete, take the number of hours sitting what is 0-1 supposed to represent? Sometimes, you have to do more research about the data you are working with before you start to work with it if the descriptions are not fully present. So, I found the person who contributed this database to UCI and his related paper in Oxford Academic at https://academic.oup.com/biolreprod/article/88/4/99,%201-8/2514098, where in fact the number of hours was scaled on 0-1 based on a min max of 0-16 hours per day. Here is a complete list of the columns and how they were normalized in this dataset:

We can see that the file does not contain column names, but just comma separated values per row/observation. Looking back at the UCI website, we can see that the real columns are

  • Season in which the analysis was performed. 1) winter, 2) spring, 3) Summer, 4) fall. (-1, -0.33, 0.33, 1)
  • Age at the time of analysis. 18-36 (0, 1)
  • Childish diseases (ie , chicken pox, measles, mumps, polio) 1) yes, 2) no. (0, 1)
  • Accident or serious trauma 1) yes, 2) no. (0, 1)
  • Surgical intervention 1) yes, 2) no. (0, 1)
  • High fevers in the last year 1) less than three months ago, 2) more than three months ago, 3) no. (-1, 0, 1)
  • Frequency of alcohol consumption 1) several times a day, 2) every day, 3) several times a week, 4) once a week, 5) hardly ever or never (0, 1)
  • Smoking habit 1) never, 2) occasional 3) daily. (-1, 0, 1)
  • Number of hours spent sitting per day ene-16 (0, 1)
  • Output: Diagnosis normal (N), altered (O)

It is always a good idea to take a look at the data file, so you can load it into a database software like Pandas properly. For example, below we will be using the Pandas function read_csv to read this comma separated data, but we want to set the header to None so we don't accidently set an observation as the column names.

Here is a bad example of loading in the data (not considering that the column names are not in the comma separated text file:

By not accounting for the file not containing the column names, we accidently set an observation as the column names (Note header defaults to 0, aka the first line in the file)! Below is the correct way to load the data, and we will be using the fertility_df for the rest of the Jupyter notebook.

plt.show()

Why did we plot without the regression you may ask? It is important to first take a look at the data and see if it looks "linear", "quadratic" etc because you don't want to assume anything about the data before you even look at it. ' You could fall prey to confirmation bias if you think it works and don't consider other options. That being said, this data does look fairly linear or possible a very very slow logarithmic function, but let's try both to see which fits better!

In [13]:
# Linear Regression
p = np.poly1d(np.polyfit(age_hours_df['age'], age_hours_df['hours_sitting_day'], 1))
xp = np.linspace(0.4, 1.2, 100)
age_hours_plot.plot(xp, p(xp), label=p, color='green')
age_hours_plot.legend()
fig
Out[13]:
In [14]:
# Wrangle data to pass into function
x_vals = list()
y_vals = list()

for index,data in age_hours_df.iterrows():
    x_vals.append(data['age'])
    y_vals.append(data['hours_sitting_day'])
In [15]:
# Run fit
scipy.optimize.curve_fit(lambda t,a,b: a+b*np.log(t),  x_vals,  y_vals)
# y ≈ 0.20271423 -0.48869888 log(x)

# Create a function to handle plotting
def log_func(x):
    return 0.20271423 - 0.48869888*np.log(x)
In [16]:
# Logistic Regression
xp = np.linspace(0.4, 1.2, 100)
ly  = list()

for x in xp:
    ly.append(log_func(x))

age_hours_plot.plot(xp, ly, label='y ≈ 0.20271423 -0.48869888 log(x)', color='red')
age_hours_plot.legend()
fig
Out[16]:

We can see that there is not much difference between the logistic and linear graphs, but the logistic one does seem to fit the data better. Also, the logistic graph will never cross zero, whereas the linear one will, in this sense the logistic graph is a better representation of real life because you can not sit for negative hours. However, it is also not very realistic near 0 because it would approach infinity. Depending on your purposes, you could be fine choosing the linear model for a situation like this, but note that the logistic model is a better representation of the real-world on the right-end and the linear model is a better representation of the real-world on the left-end.
Another thing to note is that there is a cluster of abnormal semen around 0.7 in normalized age and 0.4 in normalized hours sitting per day. Maybe we can learn from it later on in our data science pipeline!

Exploring how age relates to diagnosis
We can actually make a dot plot / number line plot with matplotlib with a little effort! I learned a lot from this StackOverflow post https://stackoverflow.com/questions/49703938/how-to-create-a-dot-plot-in-matplotlib-not-a-scatter-plot to make the below cell.

In [17]:
# Let's make a number line / dot plot of the age and see how it relates to diagnosis
values, counts = np.unique(age_hours_df['age'], return_counts=True)
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15, 5))

# Count how many are N/O diagnosis
diag = list()
for val in values:
    N = age_hours_df.loc[(age_hours_df['age'] == val) & (age_hours_df['diagnosis'] == 'N')].any(axis=1).sum()
    diag.append(N)
    
# Added to legend
legend_fulfilled = False
    
for value, count, diag in zip(values, counts, diag): 
    if legend_fulfilled == False:
        plt.plot([value]*(diag), list(range(diag)), 'go', ms=14, linestyle='', label='N')
        plt.plot([value]*(count - diag), list(range(count - diag)), 'mo', ms=14, linestyle='', label='O')
        legend_fulfilled = True
    else:
        plt.plot([value]*(diag), list(range(diag)), 'go', ms=14, linestyle='')
        plt.plot([value]*(count - diag), list(range(count - diag)), 'mo', ms=14, linestyle='')
    
for spine in ['top', 'right', 'left']:
    ax.spines[spine].set_visible(False)

ax.yaxis.set_visible(False)
ax.set_ylim(-0.5, max(counts))
ticks = list(values)
ticks.sort()
ax.set_xticks(ticks)
ax.tick_params(axis='x', pad=5, labelsize=12)
ax.set_title('Dot Plot of Normalized Age and Corresponding Diagnosis')
ax.legend()
Out[17]:
<matplotlib.legend.Legend at 0x7fd78ffa6340>

What we can learn from it:
We can see that there seems to be a cluster around 0.67 and 0.69 of altered sperm (not normal). This corresponds to 0.67*36 and .69*36 which is 24.12 and 24.84. But! We have to notice that these age groups are more represented in the data set, though still not super tall like 0.56, so if you have more people you will have more instances of not normal sperm. But this is something to take note of!

# We are going to repeat the process of what we did above as for other categorical variables in this dataset.

# Childish diseases
childish_diseases_N = N_sub[['childish_diseases', 'diagnosis']].groupby('childish_diseases').count()
childish_diseases_N.columns = ['N']
childish_diseases_O = O_sub[['childish_diseases', 'diagnosis']].groupby('childish_diseases').count()
childish_diseases_O.columns = ['O']
childish_diseases = childish_diseases_N.join(childish_diseases_O)
childish_diseases['total'] = childish_diseases['N'] + childish_diseases['O']
childish_diseases['N_normal'] = childish_diseases['N'] / childish_diseases['total']
childish_diseases['O_normal'] = childish_diseases['O'] / childish_diseases['total']

alcohol_consumption['O_normal'] = alcohol_consumption['O'] / alcohol_consumption['total']


# Smoking habits
smoking_habit_N = N_sub[['smoking_habit', 'diagnosis']].groupby('smoking_habit').count()
smoking_habit_N.columns = ['N']
smoking_habit_O = O_sub[['smoking_habit', 'diagnosis']].groupby('smoking_habit').count()
smoking_habit_O.columns = ['O']
smoking_habit = smoking_habit_N.join(smoking_habit_O)
smoking_habit['total'] = smoking_habit['N'] + smoking_habit['O']
smoking_habit['N_normal'] = smoking_habit['N'] / smoking_habit['total']
smoking_habit['O_normal'] = smoking_habit['O'] / smoking_habit['total']

Analysis, Hypothesis Testing, and ML¶

Analysis of our Visualizations and Models
In this section: I want to talk about some things we noticed from our Exploratory Data Analysis.

In terms of relationships between our numerical variables of age and number of hours sitting in a day, we found that there was approximately a linear relationship between age and the number of hours you sit in a day. Although this insight is separate from the actual diagnosis, it is still interesting to note how age and a behavior like hours sitting relates.

In terms of possible relationships between age and diagnosis of normal or abnormal sperm around 24 years old, there was a larger portion of abnormal sperm compared to other age groups. Between hours sitting in a day and diagnosis, we didn't really see a correlation between the two.

Among numerical variables: maybe age has an impact?

Now, onto our categorical variables. Earlier in our Exploratory Data Analysis, we analyzed if there were possible connections between the catgories for a particular variable and the diagnosis of sperm (normalized to be percentages out of 100). Among our visualizations, we found that season of analysis, serious accidents or trauma, high fever in the last year and alcohol consumption seemed to have the most affect on diagnosis of sperm.

Hypothesis Testing
We did a series of analyses above, but let's try to run hypothesis tests on what we thought to see if our insight is significant. I recommend looking at hypothesis tests you can do on various data science websites, here is one that I will be referencing for this tutorial: https://towardsdatascience.com/how-to-know-which-statistical-test-to-use-for-hypothesis-testing-744c91685a5d.

Here are the series of hypothesis tests we will be conducting:

    1. Hypothesis test of linear correlation between age and hours sitting (aside but interesting to see)
    1. Hypothesis test of age and diagnosis
    1. Hypothesis test of season of analysis and diagnosis
    1. Hypothesis test of serious accidents or trauma and diagnosis
    1. Hypothesis test of high fever in the last year and diagnosis
    1. Hypothesis test of alcohol consumption and diagnosis

This means for every one unit change in age (we did it on normalized, reminder from 0-36 yrs old) the odds of a normal diagnosis increases by 2.8611, and the associated p value is approximately zero, so we reject the null hypothesis that there is no relationship between age and diagnosis. However, it is important to note that this model may not be the best because of the lienar assumption between age and diagnosis, which may not be the best.

Perhaps a better test rather than this logitmodel would be a two independent samples t-test where you want to compare the means of two normally distributed independent groups. From our numerline plot above, our data looks approximately normal for N/O groups, so let's try this model/hypothesis test instead to do a different hypothesis test.

Here we found that the p-value is much higher than 0 in a previous hypothesis test. We got p = 0.207, which with a 5% significance level that there is not a statistically signficant difference between age for the Normal and Abnormal sperm groups.

Hypothesis test of season of analysis and diagnosis
Hypothesis test of serious accidents or trauma and diagnosis

Hypothesis test of alcohol consumption and diagnosis

Now, I am going to move on to hypothesis tests of
$ categorical\text{ }variable \text{ vs } diagnosis$

Because we are doing categorical vs a categorical, we should be doing a chi-squared test to see how likely it is that any observed difference between the sets arose by chance. We want to see if the sets are really independent, or that diagnosis does or does not rely on the season of analysis, serious accidents, etc. We want to use Pearson's chi square test for this purpose because we care about the differences between groups. So, we will use chi2_contingency from the statsmodels library. Here is further reading on Pearson's chi-square test of independence: https://machinelearningmastery.com/chi-squared-test-for-machine-learning/.

You may possible be thinking why not use chisquare from the statsmodels library, and that is valid. We could potentially do a chisquare test by saying that the observed values should be 50/50 for each diagnosis N/O in each group. However, that is not what we are looking for. We want to see if N/O depends on our categories for a particular variable.

Even though we only found one significant statistic, we can still try to build a model to predict diagnosis of normal and abnormal sperm. Because we are trying to predict a yes/no or normal/abnormal sperm, we should use a classification model. One such model we could use is a decision tree! This is a simple classification model that depending on certain variables, it will branch off into separate branches, eventually reaching a leaf classifying the sperm type.

How to interpret the classification report:
https://muthu.co/understanding-the-classification-report-in-sklearn/
Precision, what percentage of our classifications were correct?

  • In terms of N / normal sperm, we were about 86% correct.
  • In term of O / abnormal sperm, we were 50% correct.

Recall, what percentage of positives did you catch from the test data?

  • In terms of N / normal sperm, we caught about 96%.
  • In terms of O / abnormal sperm, we caught 20%.

As a rule of thumb, the weighted average of F1 should be used to compare classifier models, not global accuracy.

Our f1 weighted average is about 80% which is nice! This may be good for trying things out, but if you want better accuracy in the real world you may have to play around with parameters.

Note: The f1-score is a combination of precision and recall.

Insight and Policy Decision¶

We won't be making any policy decisions here, but we will be making some insights about the data we have encountered in this data science pipeline tutorial.

Regarding a connection between our numerical variables: age and hours sitting in a day, we found that there was a significant negative linear relationship between the two at least with the ages covered in this survey of 18-36 yr old people.

Fertility insights
It is quite surprising that we found the only significant variable to be accident or trauma, with more abnormal sperm found in the group with no accidents or serious trauma. Perhaps this data is skewed, especially with so few participants, or it could be that something about having a serious accident or trauma really has something to do with sperm. There is one, thing, it does warrant more investigation. In data science, you can do research and analyze data and also go back in the pipeline. This is an instance where possibly going back would be helpful, was it something with the participants themselves, or could we have done different analysis? Could we have asked this question better to see what could have happened? There are endless questions, and sometimes we have to keep on repeating different parts of the pipeline to get our answers.

As for our model, we were able to predict with about ~80% accuracy of a normal or abnormal sperm diagnosis. We tried to avoid overfitting our data by setting our minimum leaves to 2. However, that doesn't mean we were that successful. Plus, it doesn't help that our test data was imbalanced, partially because so many of the patients had normal sperm out of the 100. Perhaps more data collection can be done here.

Were we able to get great insights? Maybe, but probably not. There are more tests to be done!
